{
  "texts": [
    "All else being equal, it reflects better on you if the situation exogenously grabs and holds your attention.",
    "Finally, even if you pay the right kind of attention, in the right degree, to the right things here, you might not do so for the right reasons.",
    "If you attend to the drowning child only because you're babysitting her, for instance, and you fear legal consequences, this too would be less than ideal.",
    "3 Thus, what you attend to, how much, in what way, and for what reasons all come to bear independently on the moral assessment of your attention allocation.",
    "Moral philosophers have recently explored how attention functions for certain moral virtues (Bommarito, 2013; Chappell & Yetter-Chappell, 2016) and the role it plays in moral perception (Vance & Werner, 2022; Waggoner, 2021)."
  ]
}